âœ… Definition of Done (DoD)
Deployment & Portability
 * Single-File Logic: All logic, styles, and dependencies are vendored into one .html file.
 * Offline Execution: The app must run via file:/// protocol with zero internet access.
 * Browser Storage Partitioning:
   * localStorage: Used ONLY for small settings (<1MB) like theme and email.
   * IndexedDB: Used for models and document cache.
 * Ivanti-Friendly Sync: An explicit "Clear Local Data" and "Unload Models" function must exist to reduce profile size to <1MB before a user logs off.
Architectural Integrity (ATAM)
 * Cognitive Load: The entire app logic (excluding vendored libs) must not exceed 2500 lines of code.
 * Table of Contents: The code must maintain a clear, commented TOC at the top of the <script> tag.
 * No Compiled Tools: No TypeScript, Minifiers (for your code), or Bundlers. Raw ES6+ Javascript only.
 * Composability: Functions must be "pure" where possible (input -> output) to allow for easy extraction into a repository.
Performance & Hardware
 * WebGPU Target: Verified to run on DWR laptops and flagship Android phones (Pixel 8+, S23+) with >11GB RAM.
 * Crash-Only Design: The app saves the current "session" state to IndexedDB every 5 seconds. If the tab crashes, it reloads exactly where the user left off.
 * Manual Memory Management: The app must explicitly call .dispose() on WebGPU tensors/models when the "Unload" trigger is activated.
ðŸ›  Programming Table of Contents (Chaptered Development)
Your single file should follow this strict internal sequence to maintain maintainability, for example:
```
/* CHECKIT SINGLE-FILE APP TOC
  1. CONSTANTS & CSP CONFIG
  2. VENDORED DEPENDENCIES (pdf.js, transformers.js, docling.js)
  3. SYSTEM: IndexedDB & Model Management (Sideload/Unload)
  4. SYSTEM: State Persistence (Crash-only recovery)
  5. LOGIC: Document Processing (Deterministic / Docling)
  6. LOGIC: AI Inference (Granite Embeddings & Semantic Search)
  7. UI: Components (Heatmap, Settings, Results)
  8. UI: Event Listeners & Boot Sequence
*/
```
A note on Model Unloading
When using transformers.js with WebGPU, simply deleting the file from IndexedDB isn't enough for the current session. You must ensure the developer includes a pipeline.dispose() or similar cleanup to clear the VRAM/RAM immediately so the user can see the memory usage drop in the browser's Task Manager.

